    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 7 with a high-upside lineup tailored to exploit several soft-throwing matchups. **Yordan Alvarez** (79.83) serves as our cornerstone play today; despite a negative platoon split against Freeland, the extreme hitter-friendly environment and an ideal #2 spot in the order make him an elite start. Similarly, **Junior Caminero** (75.43) presents a strong case for offensive output against Assad, whose 4.83 xERA provides a significant efficiency boost. In the stolen base department, **Trea Turner** (69.09) remains a must-start; while he faces Robbie Ray, the combination of favorable wind conditions and his elite sprint speed gives him a high floor, even against a tough lefty arm.\n\nWe are navigating several \"Lineup Pending\" designations, specifically with **Dillon Dingler** and **Logan O'Hoppe**, whose scores remain in the marginal category. **Kazuma Okamoto** (44.09) is the most precarious active start; his score is hampered by a brutal matchup against the elite Yoshinobu Yamamoto. Our most difficult bench decision involved **Josh Smith** (43.89), who narrowly missed the cut behind **Carson Benge**. While **Josh Smith** offers versatility, his poor matchup against George Kirby\u2014who possesses an elite 3.39 xERA\u2014pushed him below our efficiency threshold. We continue to monitor the minors for **Zac Veen**, who remains ineligible for today\u2019s active roster. Owners should be wary of the volatility surrounding **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (57.18); while he projects well due to platoon advantages, his park-adjusted metrics are heavily penalized by an unfavorable hitting environment today.",
